Coalesce versus repartition, before writing.

Both of these control the number of output files, and the choice affects your write speed, your output file sizes, and the downstream read parallelism.

Coalesce with a number n does no shuffle — it is a narrow transformation. So it is fast. But the output sizes can be uneven. You use coalesce to reduce the partition count, when you do not need any rebalancing.

Repartition with a number n does a full shuffle. So it is slower. But the output sizes come out roughly equal. You use repartition to increase the partition count, or to rebalance skewed data.

The classic case is coalesce of one, then write — to produce a single output file. That is cheap. But be careful — if the upstream stage had wildly uneven partitions, that single output partition now has to hold all of the data.

So when in doubt, remember it this way. Coalesce to shrink. Repartition to grow, or to rebalance.
